canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115064"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 77-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department of a tertiary referral hospital with a 12-hour history of acute mid-thoracic back pain. He was recently diagnosed with prostate cancer and has an appointment with his urologist in a few days to discuss treatment options. The back pain was sudden in onset, worsens with movement, and is not associated with any trauma or falls. He reports no bowel or bladder dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His regular medications are amlodipine and metformin. He lives at home with his wife, is fully independent with all activities of daily living, and maintains an active social life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 138/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals mildly reduced power (4+/5) in the lower limbs, intact sensation to light touch and pinprick throughout, normal proprioception, and symmetrical deep tendon reflexes (2+) in upper and lower limbs. Plantar reflexes are downgoing bilaterally. There is no clonus. Romberg\u0027s test is negative. Gait is normal. The only other positive finding is severe mid-thoracic back pain on palpation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation for this patient\u0027s symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Plain X-ray of the thoracic spine","Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the whole spine","Bone scintigraphy","Positron emission tomography (PET) scan","Computed tomography (CT) of the thoracic spine"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture is concerning for a new metastatic lesion in the thoracic spine and the potential development of metastatic spinal cord compression, given the acute back pain and reduced power in the lower limbs. Vertebral metastases are often associated with prostate cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the whole spine\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard for detecting spinal metastases and evaluating for spinal cord compression. It provides excellent soft tissue contrast and can detect bone marrow infiltration before bony destruction is visible on other imaging modalities. Early detection is crucial for timely intervention to prevent complications such as spinal cord compression or pathological fractures. Given his excellent functional baseline, this will help guide active or palliative treatment options, including radiotherapy or surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eplain X-ray of the thoracic spine\u003C/strong\u003E would be insufficient in this case. While it might show gross bony changes, it lacks sensitivity for early metastatic disease and cannot evaluate the spinal cord or nerve roots. Whilst in practice this patient might get a plain X-ray whilst in ED, the key investigation is an MRI - and given the clinical evidence of spinal cord compression, an MRI is of paramount importance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography (CT) of the thoracic spine\u003C/strong\u003E offers better bony detail than plain X-rays but is less sensitive than MRI for early bone marrow involvement. It also provides limited soft tissue contrast compared to MRI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone scintigraphy\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful for detecting widespread bony metastases but lacks the specificity and anatomical detail provided by MRI. It would not be the first-line investigation in a patient with localised symptoms and suspected spinal involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositron emission tomography (PET) scan\u003C/strong\u003E can be valuable for staging prostate cancer and detecting distant metastases. However, it is not the most appropriate initial investigation for suspected spinal metastases, particularly when there are localised symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vertebral metastases are common in prostate cancer and can present with acute back pain.","MRI is the gold standard imaging modality for suspected spinal cord compression or vertebral metastases.","Early detection of spinal metastases is crucial for timely intervention and prevention of complications."],"references":["Kuah T, Vellayappan BA, Makmur A, Nair S, Song J, Tan JH, Kumar N, Quek ST, Hallinan JTPD. State-of-the-Art Imaging Techniques in Metastatic Spinal Cord Compression. Cancers. 2022; 14(13):3289. https://doi.org/10.3390/cancers14133289"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97072"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14095"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97072"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-22T09:00:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T09:00:03+09:30","number":10,"notes":"minor rephrasing of question","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6763"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115064"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"7912"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"